sessions.title: Building Native Apps With NativeScript
sessions.description:
NativeScript is a free and open-source runtime for building native apps using familiar tools—Angular, JavaScript/TypeScript, CSS, and npm. NativeScript renders truly native user interfaces—giving your users the best performance and UX their devices can offer.

In this workshop you’ll learn what NativeScript is, how it works, and how to use the framework to build iOS and Android apps.

The workshop is hands-on; therefore, if possible, come with NativeScript installed on your development machine and ready to go.

Come learn how to build native apps with NativeScript and Angular!

sessions.title: Welcome Keynote
sessions.description:
Come join our keynote speaker as he/she presents engaging material in a compelling way. You’ll be on the edge of your seat at the presentation slides advance one by one. You won’t believe how it ends!

Don’t miss a single breathless explanation of this award winning presentation. You’ll want to remember where you were as this riveting expository unfolds. Make sure you have your laptop fully charged so you can live blog the entire experience using real time push notification tools.

sessions.title: NativeScript loves Angular
sessions.description:
The Angular framework by Google remains one of the primary architectural choices for sophisticated organizations. The Angular framework contains a toolbox of solutions that help you standardize your JavaScript applications. Why reinvent the wheel when you can use something great right out of the box?

NativeScript allows you to write your applications using modern Angular.  In this presentation, we’ll look at how to build truly native mobile apps with NativeScript and Angular.

sessions.title: Case Study: Nationale-Nederlanden
sessions.description:
Nationale-Nederlanden Pensions launched the native app Mijn Pensioencoach a few years ago. In this session Rowdy will explain why they switched to NativeScript with Angular this year and share his experiences, struggles, challenges and victories.

You’ll get a look behind the scenes of a complex app build by a small team and because it’s a dev day, a lot of code is involved!

sessions.title: Lunch
sessions.description:
After a whole morning of learning, we bet you’ll need a bit to take it all in. You’ll want to add some food to a plate, sit with your friends and talk about the wondrous things you’ve heard today.

We have your back. We’ll make sure there are plates, and things to put on plates. We’ll also have drinks for all!

sessions.title: Plug ins and how to build them yourself
sessions.description: The NativeScript framework ships with lots of functionality. Of course, it can’t do everything, so the architects behind the NativeScript framework designed a plugin model allowing for maximal extensibility and encapsulation. Using the plugin model of NativeScript, it is easy to add any functionality you want.

sessions.title: Case Study: Triodos
sessions.description: Triodos Bank has launched an ambitious program to renew their online presence including new Mobile Banking apps. And yes ... the new banking apps are build using NativeScript and Angular. Many challenges like security, performance and code sharing across multiple apps. Winfred takes you on the Triodos journey and shares the lessons learned.

sessions.title: A new Vue for NativeScript
sessions.description: Vue is very powerful when it comes to web, but it is also a viable option for developing native mobile apps. Combining Vue with NativeScript is a great way to speed up app development. This talk will introduce you to the current state of the NativeScript and Vue integration.

sessions.title: Break
sessions.description:
I bet you need a break!

Join us for a snack and some coffee. Take a walk outside and breathe in the fresh air and beautiful scenery of Rotterdam. Use this time to recharge, repower and get your mind right. We’ve got a few more excellent presentations coming.

sessions.title: NativeScript testing with Appium
sessions.description:
There are a few things you need to know in order to build a production quality mobile application. Before shipping your shiny new application off to the world, you should ensure the application behavior is going to live up to your user’s expectations.

In this session, we’ll cover the essential steps and lessons learned shipping high quality production applications.

sessions.title: Case Study: Essent
sessions.description:
At energiedirect.nl they feel that taking care of your energy should be very easy and direct, without any hassle. That’s why they’ve introduced Regelneef. The energiedirect.nl self-service app that easily takes care of your energy.

In this session Rachèl and Jasper will be speaking about this app which was built by Essent together with Quintor and Navara using Angular and NativeScript.

sessions.title: Cool stuff: Robots and AI
sessions.description:
At some point, Earth will be ruled by robot overlords powered by AI. Why ignore this fact!

In this presentation, we’ll talk about how you can use NativeScript to operate robots. We’ll bring a robot on stage and control the robot with our phones.

After that, we’ll look at how to build AI with NativeScript. We’ll not only look at robots. we’ll look at lots of code.

sessions.title: Drinks and snacks
sessions.description:
You made it through the whole day. Wasn’t that a great line up? Let’s give a big hand to our speakers for being so well prepared. Let’s also give a hand to our attendees for being so attentive and engaging with questions.

Drinks and snacks for all!

sessions.title: Optimizing Startup Time of NativeScript Angular Apps
sessions.description:
Performance is a dreaded part of app development. This is particularly true for mobile apps where the expectations are high. We’ll explore a few methods for improving startup time for NativeScript Angular projects. Live demo included.
Topics include Lazy Loading, Webpack, AoT compilation, Minification and tree-shaking, V8 heap snapshots and Profiling startup time.

speakers.name: Rowdy Rabouw
speakers.bio:
Rowdy Rabouw is a webdeveloper with over 20 years’ experience in HTML, CSS, JavaScript and PHP.He’s a freelancer since 2004 and employed by Dutch insurance company Nationale-Nederlanden since 1992.

Rowdy started developing NativeScript apps with Angular in 2016 and running the NativeScript NL website; a curated list of courses, tools and tips to help people code awesome apps with NativeScript.

speakers.name: Sebastian Witalec
speakers.bio:
Sebastian is a Technical Evangelist for Progress/Telerik with over 9 years of experience in software engineering and architecture.

Sebastian has passion for all types of technologies. However, in the last few years his focus shifted towards cross platform Mobile development where he gained experience with Apache Cordova and NativeScript.

He is always happy to learn about the new stuff and to pass the knowledge as far as his voice (or the wire) can take him. Sebastian is based in London, UK actively working with various Dev communities in the area. When not acting techie he is a massive football fan/player (probably bigger at heart than skills).

speakers.name: Christoffer Noring
speakers.bio: Chris Noring is a London-based frontend developer with over ten years’ experience who is also a well-known speaker about NativeScript. He’s the organizer or co-organizer of six meetups and has spoken extensively about NativeScript. He also speaks abut Angular and is writing a book on Rxjs.

speakers.name: Eddy Verbruggen
speakers.bio: Eddy has worked with Progress for many years. First raising the bar for Cordova plugin quality through the Verified Plugins Marketplace, and now focusing on creating and maintaining NativeScript plugins.

speakers.name: Winfred van Egteren
speakers.bio: Winfred is full-stack developer at Triodos Bank and passionate tech geek. Started hacking Java about 20 years ago and is nowadays more focused on mobile and web development.

speakers.name: Igor Randjelovic
speakers.bio: Igor Randjelovic is a web developer, and a software engineering student. Slowly shifting focus from back-end development to front-end, due to the joy of using VueJs. Igor started developing NativeScript-Vue as his first encounter with NativeScript.

speakers.name: Rachèl Heimbach
speakers.bio:
Over the years, Rachèl has been building Angular applications and hosting Angular workshops/presentations. Back in the alpha stage of Angular, Rachèl graduated on the subject of "Angular 1.x migration to Angular 2.x". 

Last year he started investigating NativeScript’s claims about native performance and the potential of combining it with Angular.

speakers.name: Julian Steiner
speakers.bio:
Julian Steiner is a full-stack software developer by trade. Being a technology generalist, he holds a degree in Software Engineering and a Master’s in Software Engineering Management. He has successfully delivered software projects developed in JavaScript, Java, PHP and .NET, happily serving dev-teams as a Scrum Master.

He is currently helping Progress/Telerik customers finding the best solutions, while spreading the good word on technologies that spark his interest. He has been using Angular in production ever since IE7 was still officially supported and 1.0 was still a Release Candidate. Julian is based out of Cologne, Germany.

speakers.name: Jasper Boeijenga
speakers.bio:
Jasper is a senior web developer with a great passion for the frontend. As a lead developer at Essent he is responsible for the delivery of customer-oriented portals for >1.5 million users.

Last year his teams focused on the successful delivery of a NativeScript self-service app for energiedirect.nl customers.

speakers.name: Stanimira Vlaeva
speakers.bio: Stanimira is a Sofia-based Software Engineer at Progress and NativeScript core team member specializing in Angular integration and the NativeScript Webpack story.

speakers.name: Alexander Vakrilov
speakers.bio: Alex is one of the core-members to the NativeScript project team, contributing to the project since its early days. He is also co-organizer of the Angular Sofia meetup and keen on all things Angular.
